>I don't think so.  But lets suppose an attacker is trying a known
>plaintext attack.  How do you know that knowledge of the plaintext and
>ciphertext doesn't give you some small peice of information about the
>IV, which now gives you a peek inside the encryption of the previous
>block.
>I am nervous about using any internal information from the encryption,
>in any way.
 
   Yes, definitely.  Off the top of my head, I can't see a good way of
using those 4th round intermediary values against you, since they *are*
being re-encrypted with the full 8 rounds before I see them.  But it
gives me the willies to take a chance at exposing 4th-round values like
that.
 
